{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_chimera_ver01/data/sn92067029/00516998556/1908030501/0076.xml":{"full_text":"The gusx Jerald.\nJ. E. AND L. H. MAYES. Publishers.\nOURONLY TEKMB.\nOne Year (in advance,) $2.00\nEntered November 17, 1803, st Lnik, Wyoming, M\nMOond-o? u matter, tinder Aoi of Oongreu of\nKerch 3,1879.\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 5, 1908.\nWho ever suspected there would\nbe a lease law? We didn\u2019t.\nThe spring freshet season brings\nno consolation to the arid portion of\nthe south.\nProsperity seems to have returned\njust in time to meet the Easter bon\nnet in the road and get held up.\nThe 320 acre Mondell homestead\nbill is going to become a law\u2014and\nshe\u2019ll be a booster for Wyoming.\nIn spite of the fact that leap year\nis pretty well advanced, there is no\nindication yet who Miss Democracy\nis going to propose to.\nConsidering the troubles that arc\nlooming up for the next administra\ntion, the wonder is that so many\npeople should be hunting for the job.\nA Kentucky woman is asking for\na divorce so that she can marry the\nghost of Bob Ingersoll. And Bob\nalways professed to believe that the\ndead were forever at rest.\nHaving taken all the credit for\nthe recent panic, it is about time\nfor Tom Lawson to begin a series of\nmagazine articles on how he brought\nabout the return of prosperity.\nA Chicago man was accepted\nafter proposing 365 times in one\nyear, and after three months of\nmarried life he applied for a divorce\non the ground of cruelty. A man\nwho won\u2019t take \u201cno\" for an answer\nsometimes lives to regret it.\nThis paper is opposed to a lease\nor any permit law, or any law that\nwill give the big outfit a chance to\nhold government land and prevent\nthe settlement of it. Deer creek\nvalley near Glenrock, with its thou\nsands of acres of leased laud, is a liv\ning example of what a lease law will\ndo to prevent settlement. A lease 1\nlaw that will prevent the range hog\nfrom getting control can never be\nenacted. Better have a sore toe 1\nthan have your leg cut off.\nIt now looks very much as though\nthe 320 acre homestead bill will pass\nboth bouses of congress and become\na law before the adjournment of\nthat body. It has passed the public\nlands committee, which almost in\nsures its final passage. If it does\nbecome a law the range hog will\nhave to clear the decks and make\nroom for the great influx of immi-\ngration to Wyoming, which will\nsurely come. And then where, oh,\nwhere, will the lease fiends be?\nThe Laramie Republican says\nthere is \u201cnothin doin\u2019\u2019 in the home\nstead line in Albany county. No\nwonder, with every alternate section\ntakeu by the Union Pacific railroad,\na mountain range traveling the\ncounty, ^bd the plains itself with an\nelevation of over 7,000 feet; then 1\nthrow in some leased land and forest\nreserves and it is no wonder there is 1\nnothing left. Do the people of Con- 1\nverse county want some 2x4 \u201ckid\"\nfrom some eastern school to tell\nthem bow to run their stock busi\nness? If so, then follow the Repub\nlican's advice.\n1\nThe administration organs make 1\na great fuss about alleged land 1\nfrauds, seeking to create the im\npression that it is assuming gigantic\nproportions, while the fact is that 1\nland frauds are uot one tenth what\nthey were 25 or 30 years ago. The\nwhole thing is a scheme of Baron\nPinchot aud his crowd of pap suck\ners in trying to prevent people from\ntaking up laud by making it so bur\ndensome that the expense will be\ngreater than the value of the land.\nBv this means they hope to get all\nthe government land included in\none great hunting reserve for the\nBaron and his rich eastern friends\nou the plea of preserving forests,\nand then make the stockmen pay\nfor keeping it up for them\nPVT OUARANTEE BEHIND BANKS-\nThere promises to be a stubborn\nfight over currency legislation, just\nas was outlined at the beginning of\nthe session of congress, and possibly\nthe result will be no legislation at\nall\u2014just what Speaker Cannon and\na number of other house and senate\nleaders have been hoping. The lead\ning measure that lias been put for\nward so far is the so-called Aldrich\nbill, providing for not more than\n$250,000,000 worth of bank note\ncirculation based on state, munici\npal and railroad bonds. These notes\nare to be subject to a tax of half of\none per cent a month so long as\nthey are outstanding. This scheme\nis pronounced by some of the finan\ncial leaders to be an amateurish\nmakeshift. Chairman Fowler, of\nthe house committee on banking\nand currency, is much opposed to\nthe plans and favors the establish\nment of a central bank of issue\nsomewhat similar to the imperial\nbanks of the continent.\nHe would have it located in Chi\ncago as being nearest the geopraph\nical centre of the country and being\nin a position better to meet the de\nmands of the middle and far west\nand tending to divorce the money\ncontrol of the country from New\nYork, where it is well known all the\nrelief furnished in the various panics\nhave been carefully locked up till\nNew York was well on its financial\nfeet, irrespective of what the rest\nof the country needed or wanted.\nThere will be a fight against the\nAldrich bill. The west and south are\nlined up against it aud there will be\na lot of talk, which is equivalent to\ndelay.\nIt would seem that the simplest,\nand possibly the most effective sug\ngestion so far made, is that of Mr.\nBryan, who favors putting the gov\nernment guarantee behind bank de\nposits and thus restoring public\nconfidence. This restoration of con\nfidence is really the thing that is\nneeded after all for there has been\nmore than $81,000,000 of foreign\ngold imported during the panic, and\nthis together with the Panama bond\nissue gives us more money in the\ncountry than there was before the\nflurry commenced.\nTHE AMERICAN NAVY.\nCriticism of the navy has become\nso much the fashion recently that\nthe president sometime ago deputed\nRear Admiral Converse, now on the\nretired list, to go into the question\nfrom the standpoint of an expert\nand tell the truth for the benefit of\nthe public. It will be remembered\nby those who have followed the naval\ndiscussion that a lot of so-called ex\nperts have made all sorts of charges\nagainst the navy from defective con\nstruction and material to lack of\nspeed aud gun practice. The two\nlatter charges are, as almost every\none knows, unfounded. The Ameri\ncan navy now holds the record for\ntarget practice with almost all guns\nat almost all distances. Ship for\nship, the shooting average is better\nthan in any nation of the world, and\nthe speed of the later ships has\nproved in each class to be the high\nest class that could be expected. In\nfact there are only two varieties of\nwarship where the American navy\nhas not kept in the first flight as to\nspeed. This is in some of the very\npowerful destroyers where the speed\nrecord is held just now by the Ger\nman navy and in some of the fast\ncruising scout ships recently turned\nout by the English Admiralty.\nThese are matters that come\nwithin the ken of the average lay\nman. Admiral Converse, however,\ngoes into the more technical details\nof construction. He says that some\nof the older ships of the navy are\nundoubtedly not up to the latest\nmodels in construction. They were\nexperiments in their time as in real\nity all warships are. But the prac\ntical lessons of the Russo-Japanese\nwar have been taken into considera\ntion in all of the later naval con\nstruction, and as to army protection,\nload line, height of freeboard and\ngun position, there is no fault to be\nfound with any of the American\nships. Squadron for squadron, they\nwould be able to holdthelrown with\nany navy in the world. This Is good\nbearing coming from a man like Ad\nmiral Converse, for he Is an officer\naud a gentleman and a man who\nknows his profession infinitely better\nthan the professional magazine\nwriter.\nManville Notes\nC. W. Onyon of Lost Springs, was\nin town Wednesday.\nRev. W. S. Young is spending\nthe week in Douglas.\nMiss Julia Card spent a few days\nlast week at Douglas.\nW. N. Shippen, who has been\nquite sick for several weeks, is re\ncovering.\ni Dr. and Mrs. McCreery went up\nto the county seat Monday for a\nfew days.\n1 Miss Wright and Miss Ballard\nspent last Sunday at the home of\nMr. and Mrs. L. D. Wilson.\nMrs. G. G. Allen came down from\nLost Springs last Thursday and re\nmained a short time with friends.\nMrs. Roy Baughn went np to\nDouglas last Tuesday and spent\na few days with Mrs. C. E. Baker.\nMr. and Mrs. Geo. Carroll and\nchildren, of Douglas, visited over\nSunday with Mr. and Mrs. S. H.\nCase.\nMr. and Mrs. W. P. Spaugh re\nturned the first of the week from\na visit of several weeks at Grand\nIsland.\nThe entertainment, which was\ngiven last Friday evening by home\ntalent, was well attended and was\ni quite interesting and amusing.\nMr. Lot Brown, of Chicago, aud\n1 Mr. Oscar Brown, of Salt Lake City,\nwho were here settling up the af\nfairs of their mother, Mrs. R. S.\nBrown, left last week for their re\nspective homes.\nThe following resolutions of re\nspect were adopted by Niobrara\ncamp No. 3264, R. N. A. of A., Man\nville, Wyoming.\nWhereas, Our Heavenly Father,\nin His wisdom, has called from our\nmidst our first receiver and one of\nour charter members, Mrs. R. S.\nBrown, therefore,\nResolved, That we, the members\nof this camp will ever remember her\nacts of kindness and her faithful*\nI ness to our camp, and further,\nResolved, That we extend the\nsympathy of the camp to her rela\ntives and friends; also\nResolved, That our charter be\ndraped in mourning for 60 days and\na copy of these resolutions be spread\non the minutes of our camp.\nLizzie E. Spauoh.\nSadie E. Roush.\nLizzie K. Manoroan.\nNorthview News.\nHenry Moravick is up from Harri\nson.\nTom Wilsou is having some lum\nber sawed and is hauling logs for a\nnew house.\ni Mrs. Glenn and her daughter, Mrs.\nWilson, visited for several days on\nOld Woman creek.\nThere will be a dance at Fred\nDale's oldTanch on the mouth of\nAlkali on Friday, March 6tb.\nTom Wilson\u2019s hounds gave a wolf\nsuch a rough handling that it went\n1 in its hole, where Tom smoked it to\ndeath, then pulled it out.\nIf anyone has any doubts about\nhow the ranchers feel towards the\nlease law fiends, let them get out\nand listen to the profanity headed\ntheir way.\nA thunder shower passed down\nCheyenne river on the last day of\nFebruary. It was the real thing as\nit was accompanied by thunder,\nlightning and rain.\nThere will probably be a call for\ntwo more schools in this district at\ni the next school meeting. With but\nenough money to run the three\nschools that are now established,\nwe need more assessable property or\nelse to get up a scheme to bunch\nthe settlers.\nA very nice school entertainment\nwas given by Miss Larsen, at the\nElmer Brown school bouse Saturday\nuight, in which the children of her\nschool and some of the growups\nI participated, Mrs. Marchant fur*\nnisbing lustrumentai music. There\nwere some very nice recitations,\ntableaus and dialogues. A very\nI nice lunch was served, and after the\nliterary roundup Albert Herman\nand Billy Blair furnished some ex\ncellent music for those who wished\nto dance. Those who attended re\nport having a very nice time.\nCLOSING OUT SALE\nFor cash on all the following goods. These\n\u2022r are not old goods, but almost new:\nMEN'S WINTER UNDERWEAR.\nV All wool heavy underwear, regular value $4.50 a suit, now Y\ntp going at \u2022\u25a0\u2022J\u00ae\nAy All wool line underwear, regular value $4.50 a suit, going at 3.50 Ay\nExtra line Camel\u2019s hair, regular value $2.75, going at. 2.20 JI\nFine natural wool, regular value $2.25, going at 1.90\nMen\u2019s fleece-lined, regular value $1.25, going at. 1.00 w\nA. Men's all wool overshirts, regular price $3.00, each going Ay\nat $2.48; regular $2.25 shirts at slo.>; $2.00 shirts at a\n$1.65; $1 shirts at 85 cents; 90 cent shirts at 75 cents.\nMen's English Corduroy pants, regular price $4.50, going at V\nA $3.95. Also all men's overshoes, shoes, boots, socks, leg-\ngings, etc., going at the same very low prices\u2014in fact\nall our ladies'and children's shoes, underwear, furs, rugs,\netc., are going at nearly cost.\n\nGROCERIES.\ntLots of bargains in Groceries, such as cash can only buy. 1\nWe will hereafter have two prices, one for cash and one for\ncredit. The person with the cash reaps the benefit.\ng k\nA FEW SPECIALS. O\nf 4\nGood kerosene at 23 cents a gallon. Try a gallon. I guar-\nantee it all to burn. Seven packages of breakfast food for sl.\nWhite Star Coffee, regular price 40 cents a pound, now3s cents, t\n.f. Thread, regular price 2 spools for 15 cents, during this sale z\nj going at 5 cents a spool. Come early and get your choice ol\nV the bargains. Remember this is a cash sale and we save you 11\nmoney. At 9\n\u2022W. H. Millburn\u2019s Store,:\n2 LUSK. WYOMING. A\nTHE STAR\nmbit 1 JaL shop.\nHaircut 35 Bath.. 35\nShave .15 Tonic 10\nShampoo .35 W Razors honed. ...35\nMassage .35 Terms strictly cash.\nW. A. KIMBALL, Proprietor, Lusk, W\u2019yoming.\nSMBEATinware. Saddles.\n7 Harn cm. Etc. 1\nLusk, Wyoming.\n+++*-i--y++++++++*+*+++++-y++-:-+*+**<++^\nPURITAN RYE,\nIT\u2019S ALL RIGHT. I\ne^Gdararpteed tlpder tl?e Pare Food i\nD. SACHS SONS, Sole Controllers, Louisville, Ky. 2\nWM. A. HOLSAPPLE, Distributer, Lusk, Wyoming, x\nW F. LOUGER^Jf WWsji\ng and Undertaking Goods Q\nW. F. LOUGER. Lusk, Wyoming.\nTHE HERALD Does Job Printing Right.","height":"20372","width":"13748"}}
